<section xml:id="floatingpoint-math_vocabulary"
         xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Vocabulary</title>
  <p>
    <dl>
      <li>
        <title>floating-point:</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>floating-point</h>
          </idx> A data type that represents numbers with an
          integer part and a fractional part. In C++, the default floating-point type is <c>double</c>.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>rounding error:</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>rounding error</h>
          </idx> The difference between the number we want to
          represent and the nearest floating-point number.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>type cast:</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>type cast</h>
          </idx> An operation that explicitly converts one data type
          into another. In Java, it appears as a type name in parentheses, like <c>(int)</c>.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>literal:</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>literal</h>
          </idx> A value that appears in source code. For example, <c>"Hello"</c>
          is a string literal, and <c>74</c> is an integer literal.</p>
      </li>
      <li> 
        <title>magic number:</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>magic number</h>
          </idx> A number that appears without explanation as part of
          an expression. It should generally be replaced with a constant.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>constant:</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>constant</h>
          </idx> A variable, declared as <c>const</c>, whose value cannot be
          changed.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>NaN:</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>NaN</h>
          </idx> A special floating-point value that stands for <q>not a
          number</q>.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Inf:</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>INFINITY</h>
          </idx> A special floating-point value that stands for <q>too large to store</q>.</p>
      </li>
    </dl>
  </p>
</section>